gland":"Herefordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"c.1435–about1490":"circa 1435–circa 1490","1435–1490":"1435–1490","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1436–Female":"1436–Overleden","1450–1490":"1450–1490","1460–1540":"1460–1540","1330–Male":"1330–Overleden","1336–Female":"1336–Overleden","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","about1490":"circa 1490","1336":"1336","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1540":"1540","9 January 1460":"9 januari 1460","1428":"1428","c.1435":"circa 1435","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"c.1435–about1490":"about 1435–about 1490","1435–1490":"1435–1490","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1436–Female":"1436–Deceased","1450–1490":"1450–1490","1460–1540":"1460–1540","1330–Male":"1330–Deceased","1336–Female":"1336–Deceased","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","about1490":"about 1490","1336":"1336","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1540":"1540","9 January 1460":"9 January 1460","1428":"1428","c.1435":"about 1435","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Abbott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>abbod</i>, <i>abbot(t)</i>, <i>abbat</i> ‘abbot’ (Old English <i>abbod</i>) or Old French <i>abet</i> ‘priest’. Both the Old English and the Old French term are derived from Late Latin <i>abbas</i> (genitive <i>abbatis</i>) ‘priest’, from Greek <i>abbas</i>, from Aramaic <i>aba</i> ‘father’. The nickname was presumably a joking reference to a person's behaviour. In the US, the English name is also sometimes a translation of a cognate or equivalent European name, e.g. Italian   Abate  , Spanish   Abad  , or German   Abt  .","History: George Abbot from Yorkshire, England, settled in Andover, MA, in 1640; he had numerous prominent descendants. George Abbott (probably not the same man) died in Rowley, MA, in 1647. Another early migrant was James Abbott, who came from Somerset, England, to Long Island, NY, in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Abate","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Antonio, Carmelo, Carmine, Gaetano, Vito, Angelo, Canio, Rocco, Sal, Aldo, Carlo.","Italian: from <i>abate</i> ‘priest’ (from Late Latin <i>abbas</i> ‘priest’, genitive <i>abbatis</i>). It could be a nickname, perhaps given to someone who behaved in a priest-like manner, an occupational name for the servant of a priest, or it may denote an (illegitimate) son of a priest. Compare   Labate  ."]},{"name":"Abbot","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Abbott  . The spelling with one <i>-t</i> is more typically Scottish than English, and in Gaelic-speaking areas of Scotland, this is sometimes an Anglicized form of   McNabb  ."]},{"name":"Abbitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Abbott  ."]},{"name":"Abbett","meanings":["English: variant of   Abbott  ."]},{"name":"Abbotts","meanings":["English:","topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>(atte) abbotes</i> ‘(at the, of the) abbot's (house or quarters)’, a name for someone who lived or worked at such a place, presumably a servant.","variant of   Abbott  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":20,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Abbott II was born about 1435, in Suffolk, England, his father, John Abbott, was 106 and his mother, Mrs. John Abbott II, was 100. He married Alice Anne Gare in 1450, in Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1490, in Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England, at the age of 57."},"et":{"c.1435–about1490":"umbes 1435–umbes 1490","1435–1490":"1435–1490","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1436–Female":"1436–Surnud","1450–1490":"1450–1490","1460–1540":"1460–1540","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1336–Female":"1336–Surnud","1330":"1330","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1436":"1436","about1490":"umbes 1490","1336":"1336","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1540":"1540","9 January 1460":"9. jaanuar 1460","1428":"1428","c.1435":"umbes 1435","Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Baconsthorpe, Norfolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"c.1435–about1490":"noin 1435–noin 1490","1435–1490":"1435–1490","1428–1460":"1428–1460","1436–Female":